nal Airport|Minneapolis, Minnesota]]|| 590,000 || Delta, Southwest, Spirit, Sun Country\n|}\n\n===Top airlines by international passengers===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|+ Top airlines by international passengers carried at McCarran Airport (2017)\n|-\n! Rank\n! Airline\n! Passengers (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mccarran.com/fsweb/file/404082/2017%20Total%20Passengers.pdf|title=2017 Statistics - Enplaned and Deplaned Passengers|publisher=McCarran International Airport|page=1|accessdate=June 6, 2018|date=January 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124070606/https://www.mccarran.com/fsweb/file/404082/2017%20Total%20Passengers.pdf|archive-date=2018-01-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1 || [[WestJet]] || 921,950\n|-\n| 2 || [[Air Canada Rouge]] || 862,403\n|-\n| 3 || [[British Airways]] || 320,580\n|-\n| 4 || [[Virgin Atlantic]] || 284,183\n|-\n| 5 || [[Aerom\u00e9xico]] || 200,474\n|-\n| 6 || [[Volaris]] || 176,444\n|-\n| 7 || [[Interjet]] || 173,281\n|-\n| 8 || [[Thomas Cook Airlines]] || 136,291\n|-\n| 9 || [[Korean Air]] || 116,240\n|-\n| 10 || [[Copa Airlines]] || 97,748\n|}\n\n===Annual traffic===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Annual passenger traffic at LAS<br />1997\u2013Present'''<ref name=\"LAS-Stat\">{{cite web |title=Statistics at Clark County Department of Aviation |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Business/Statistics?id=7429 |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n! Year !! Passengers !! Year !! Passengers !! Year !! Passengers\n|-\n| 1997||30,315,094||2007||47,728,414||2017||48,500,194\n|-\n| 1998||30,227,287||2008||44,074,707||2018||49,716,584 \n|-\n| 1999||33,715,129||2009||40,469,012||2019||51,537,638\n|-\n| 2000||36,865,893||2010||39,757,359||2020||\n|-\n| 2001||35,180,960||2011||41,479,814||2021||\n|-\n| 2002||35,009,011||2012||41,667,596||2022||\n|-\n| 2003||36,265,932||2013||41,857,059||2023||\n|-\n| 2004||41,441,531||2014||42,885,350||2024||\n|-\n| 2005||44,267,362||2015||45,389,074||2025||\n|-\n| 2006||46,193,329||2016||47,435,640||2026||\n|}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On the evening of November 15, 1964, [[Bonanza Air Lines Flight 114]], a [[Fairchild F-27]] turboprop  flying from [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport]] to McCarran Int'l Airport crashed into the top of a hill in desert country about {{convert|8|mi}} SSW of Las Vegas in poor weather conditions, all 26 passengers and three crew perished. The probable cause was the misreading of a faulty, outdated approach chart by the captain which resulted in a premature descent before impacting terrain.<ref>{{ASN accident|id=19641115-0|title=N745L|wikibase=no}}</ref>\n* On September 8, 2015, [[British Airways Flight 2276]] aborted takeoff from McCarran due to engine failure. While preparing to takeoff from runway 7L for London [[Gatwick Airport]], the [[Boeing 777-200ER]] suffered failure of its left ([[Aircraft engine position number|#1]]) engine, and a fire erupted.<ref name=\"ibt2276\">{{cite news |last=Lidgett |first=Adam |date=September 8, 2015 |title=British Airways Plane Fire Update: Runway 7L At Las Vegas Airport Reopens After Plane Fire That Left 14 People Injured |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/british-airways-plane-fire-update-runway-7l-las-vegas-airport-reopens-after-plane-2088015 |work=[[International Business Times]] |access-date=May 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604103207/http://www.ibtimes.com/british-airways-plane-fire-update-runway-7l-las-vegas-airport-reopens-after-plane-2088015 |archive-date=June 4, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> 14 passengers suffered injuries during the evacuation,<ref name=\"ibt2276\" /> and the runway was closed for eight hours.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Rebecca |title=Runway reopens after British Airways plane catches fire at Las Vegas airport |url=http://www.ktnv.com/news/runway-reopens-after-british-airways-plane-catches-fire-at-las-vegas-airport |work=[[KTNV-TV]] |access-date=May 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603221151/http://www.ktnv.com/news/runway-reopens-after-british-airways-plane-catches-fire-at-las-vegas-airport |archive-date=2016-06-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The aircraft suffered major damage, but it was repaired and returned to service in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |date=March 24, 2016 |title=British Airways B777-200ER G-VIIO Returns to Service |url=http://www.thebasource.com/british-airways-b777-200er-g-viio-returns-to-service/ |work=The BA Source |access-date=May 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609201750/http://www.thebasource.com/british-airways-b777-200er-g-viio-returns-to-service/ |archive-date=June 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite report |last=Jones |first=Chris |date=2012 |title=Terminal 3 Media Kit |url=https://www.mccarran.com/T3-Information/files/t3%20press%20kit.pdf |publisher=McCarran International Airport |accessdate=May 1, 2016 |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325181650/https://www.mccarran.com/T3-Information/files/t3%20press%20kit.pdf |archivedate=March 25, 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Moehring |first1=Eugene |last2=Green |first2=Michael |date=2005 |title=Las Vegas: A Centennial History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQ7mORxm6TYC |location=Reno, NV |publisher=[[University of Nevada Press]] |isbn=0-87417-615-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wright |first=Frank |date=2005 |title=Nevada Yesterdays: Short Looks at Las Vegas History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VD0e59nXb6MC |location=Las Vegas, NV |publisher=Stephens Press |isbn=1-932173-27-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Zook |first1=Lynn |last2=Sandquist |first2=Allen |last3=Burke |first3=Carey |date=2009 |title=Las Vegas, 1905-1965 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MrDckUPM0nIC |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=978-0-7385-6969-7 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.mccarran.com/}}\n* {{FAA-diagram|00662}}\n* {{FAA-procedures|LAS}}\n* [http://www.clarkcountynv.gov/Depts/parks/Pages/cannon-aviation-museum.aspx Howard W. Cannon Aviation Museum] {{mdash}} Official site\n* [[Jeppesen]] airport diagrams for [https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8041962050/sizes/l 1955] and [https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8066233386/sizes/l 1966]\n{{US-airport|LAS}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Aviation}}\n{{Major US Airports}}\n{{Las Vegas Valley}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mccarran International Airport}}\n[[Category:McCarran International Airport|*]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Airports in Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Paradise, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Transportation in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Airport near Las Vegas, Nevada, United States}}\n{{Redirect|Las Vegas Airport|the airport in Las Vegas, New Mexico|Las Vegas Municipal Airport}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = McCarran International Airport\n| image = McCarran International Airport.png\n| image-width = 250\n| image2 = Las Vegas McCarran.jpg\n| image2-width = 250\n| caption2 = The airport in 2012\n| IATA = LAS\n| ICAO = KLAS\n| FAA = LAS\n| WMO = 72386\n| type = Public\n| owner = [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]]\n| operator = [[Clark County Department of Aviation]]\n| city-served = [[Las Vegas Valley]], Southern Utah, [[Southern Nevada]], [[Northern Arizona]]\n| location = [[Paradise, Nevada]], United States\n| elevation-f = 2,181\n| elevation-m = 665\n| coordinates = {{coord|36|04|48|N|115|09|08|W|region:US-NV|display=inline,title}}\n| website = {{URL|www.mccarran.com|mccarran.com}}\n| pushpin_map = United States Downtown Las Vegas#USA Nevada#USA#North America\n| pushpin_label = '''LAS'''\n| r1-number = 1L/19R\n| r1-length-f = 8,988\n| r1-length-m = 2,740\n| r1-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 51,537,638\n| stat-year = 2019\n| focus_city = * [[Allegiant Air]]\n* [[Frontier Airlines]]\n* [[JSX (airline)|JSX]]\n* [[Southwest Airlines]]\n* [[Spirit Airlines]]\n* [[Sun Country Airlines]]\n| r2-number = 1R/19L\n| r2-length-f = 9,771\n| r2-length-m = 2,978\n| r2-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| r3-number = 8L/26R\n| r3-length-f = 14,515\n| r3-length-m = 4,424\n| r3-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| r4-number = 8R/26L\n| r4-length-f = 10,525\n| r4-length-m = 3,208\n| r4-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 552,962\n| stat3-header = Cargo\n| stat3-data = 264,259,792 lbs.\n| footnotes = Source: McCarran International Airport<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mccarran.com/Business/Statistics?id=7405 |title= Clark County Department of Aviation Statistics |publisher= McCarran.com |accessdate= 1 February 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190202095143/https://www.mccarran.com/Business/Statistics?id=7405 |archive-date= 2 February 2019 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''McCarran International Airport''' {{Airport codes|LAS|KLAS|LAS}} is an [[international airport]] in [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]] and is the main airport for public and military use in the [[Las Vegas Valley]], a metropolitan area in the U.S. state of Nevada, about {{Convert|5|mi}} south of [[Downtown Las Vegas]]. The airport is owned by [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]] and operated by the [[Clark County Department of Aviation]]. It is named after the late [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Pat McCarran]], a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] who contributed to the development of aviation both in Las Vegas and on a national scale. LAS covers 2,800 acres (11.3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) of land.<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=LAS|use=PU|own=PU|site=27013.1*A}}, effective February 1, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe airport was built in 1942 and opened to airline flights in 1948. It has expanded since then and has employed various innovative technologies, such as common-use facilities. The airport has four runways and two passenger terminals. East of the passenger terminals is the Marnell Air Cargo Center, and on the west side of the airport are [[fixed-base operator]]s and helicopter companies.\n\nThe airport has nonstop flights to cities in North America, Europe, and Asia. It is an operating base for [[Allegiant Air]] and a crew and maintenance base for [[Frontier Airlines]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/frontier-adding-las-vegas-flights-local-crew-base/|title=Frontier adding Las Vegas flights, local crew base|date=4 May 2017|access-date=5 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505084328/https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/frontier-adding-las-vegas-flights-local-crew-base/|archive-date=5 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Southwest Airlines]], and [[Spirit Airlines]].\n\n==History==\n===Origins (1920\u20131948)===\n[[File:U.S. Senator Pat McCarran handing mail bag to Pony Express rider, Dedication Ceremony, McCarran Air Field, Las Vegas, Nevada (74665).jpg|thumb|Postcard showing Senator McCarran at the original McCarran Field, 1941]]\nThe first airport at Las Vegas was [[Anderson Field (Nevada)|Anderson Field]], opened in November 1920<ref name=\"clarkcounty\">{{cite web |title=Howard W. Cannon Aviation Museum |url=http://www.clarkcountynv.gov/parks/Pages/cannon-aviation-museum.aspx |work=[[Clark County, Nevada]] |access-date=April 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503175241/http://www.clarkcountynv.gov/parks/pages/cannon-aviation-museum.aspx |archive-date=May 3, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Wright|2005|page=31}} southeast of present-day Sahara Ave and Paradise Rd. Purchased by the Rockwell brothers in 1925, the airfield was renamed Rockwell Field, and in April 1926 [[Western Air Express]] (WAE) began carrying mail (and eventually passengers).<ref name=\"clarkcounty\"/> When the brothers sold Rockwell Field and the new owner canceled WAE's lease, the airline had to look for another airport.{{sfn|Moehring|Green|2005|page=73}} Local businessman P. A. Simon had built an airfield northeast of the city{{sfn|Moehring|Green|2005|page=73}} (now [[Nellis Air Force Base]]) and WAE moved there in November 1929 and bought the field a few years later.{{sfn|Wright|2005|page=32}}{{sfn|Moehring|Green|2005|pages=85, 145}}\n\nWhen the city tried to buy the field and build a more modern terminal, WAE refused, but with the advent of World War II WAE was pressured to sell.{{sfn|Moehring|Green|2005|pages=85\u201386}} Nevada Senator [[Pat McCarran]] helped obtain federal funding for the city to buy the field and build a terminal. He also helped establish a gunnery school by the [[United States Army Air Corps]] at the field.{{sfn|Wright|2005|page=33}} For the senator's contributions, the airport was named McCarran Field in 1941.<ref name=\"one1\">{{cite web |last=Hall-Patton |first=Mark |date=September 27, 2010 |title=McCarran International Airport |url=http://www.onlinenevada.org/articles/mccarran-international-airport |work=Online Nevada Encyclopedia |access-date=April 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426215519/http://www.onlinenevada.org/articles/mccarran-international-airport |archive-date=April 26, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA third airfield, Alamo Field, was established in 1942 by aviator George Crockett south of Las Vegas, at the present location of McCarran Airport.{{sfn|Wright|2005|page=35}} The Army sought to open a base at the site of McCarran Field, so Clark County purchased Alamo Field to make it its airline airport. Alamo Field became the new McCarran Field on December 19, 1948.<ref name=\"one1\"/>{{sfn|Wright|2005|page=35}} Meanwhile, the Army reopened its base at the original McCarran Field in 1949 and named it [[Nellis Air Force Base]] in 1950.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hall-Patton |first=Mark |date=September 27, 2010 |title=Las Vegas Army Air Base |url=http://onlinenevada.org/articles/las-vegas-army-air-base |work=Online Nevada Encyclopedia |access-date=April 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429042500/http://www.onlinenevada.org/articles/las-vegas-army-air-base |archive-date=April 29, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Early expansion (1949\u20131996)===\nIn its first year of operation McCarran Field served over 35,000 passengers. The April 1949 OAG shows 12 departures a day: 5 Western, 5 TWA and 2 United. The [[Las Vegas#Economy|Las Vegas casino industry]] grew during the 1950s, and the airport handled 959,603 passengers in 1959.<ref name=\"one1\"/> The May 1959 OAG shows 47 weekday departures: 13 Western, 11 United, 11 TWA, 9 Bonanza and 3 Pacific. The first jet flights were United 720s in September 1960.\n\n[[File:EM A-Gates (2596522453).jpg|thumb|right|A Gates and rotunda area with slot machines in 2007]]\nAirport officials began planning a new passenger terminal; the original terminal was on [[Las Vegas Boulevard]], and the new one was built on Paradise Road.{{sfn|Zook|Sandquist|Burke|2009|page=73}} The terminal, whose design was inspired by the [[TWA Flight Center]] in New York City,{{sfn|Zook|Sandquist|Burke|2009|page=73}} opened on March 15, 1963.<ref name=\"one1\"/> The airport was renamed McCarran International Airport in September 1968.{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=15}} Further expansion took place between 1970 and 1974 with the construction of the A and B gates.\n\nBefore deregulation the airport had four dominant carriers: [[United Airlines|United]] and [[Trans World Airlines|TWA]] served both coasts nonstop, while [[Western Airlines|Western]] and [[Hughes Airwest]] flew to cities in the western US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.departedflights.com/LAS75intro.html|title=LAS75intro|website=www.departedflights.com|access-date=2018-10-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181101015753/http://www.departedflights.com/LAS75intro.html|archive-date=2018-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref> After the airline industry was [[Airline Deregulation Act|deregulated]] in 1978, the number of airlines at McCarran doubled from seven to fourteen by the end of 1979.<ref name=\"one1\" /> New airlines included [[American Airlines|American]], [[Braniff International Airways|Braniff]] and [[Continental Airlines|Continental]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.departedflights.com/LAS79intro.html|title=LAS79intro|website=www.departedflights.com|access-date=2018-10-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181101015739/http://www.departedflights.com/LAS79intro.html|archive-date=2018-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response, the county launched an expansion plan, McCarran 2000, listing projects to be undertaken into the year 2000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Galatz |first=Karen |date=December 6, 1978 |title=Commissioners OK $216 Mil. McCarran expansion |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1978/dec/06/commissioners-ok-216-mil-mccarran-expansion/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503004552/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1978/dec/06/commissioners-ok-216-mil-mccarran-expansion/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> Expanded baggage claim facilities, an esplanade, and a parking garage opened in 1985; the C Gates and the first line of the [[McCarran International Airport Automated People Movers|people mover system]] followed in 1987.{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=15}}\n\nThe Charter/International Terminal, later renamed Terminal 2, opened in December 1991 to handle international traffic.{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=15}} An additional, nine-story parking garage and a [[McCarran Airport Connector|tunnel]] linking the [[Las Vegas Beltway]] to the airport were constructed as well.<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=October 31, 1996 |title=Colorful McCarran Airport Parking Plaza opens Tuesday |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/oct/31/colorful-mccarran-airport-parking-plaza-opens-tues/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016194049/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/oct/31/colorful-mccarran-airport-parking-plaza-opens-tues/ |archive-date=October 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |date=Spring 1995 |volume=58 |issue=4 |title=Las Vegas Airport Connector Opens |url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/publications/publicroads/95spring/alongroad.cfm |magazine=Public Roads |publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513142137/http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/publications/publicroads/95spring/alongroad.cfm |archive-date=May 13, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In June 1998, the southwest and southeast wings of the D Gates were opened.<ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Jace |date=June 15, 1998 |title=New terminal reminder of earlier times, family city |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/jun/15/new-terminal-reminder-of-earlier-times-family-city/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005041/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/jun/15/new-terminal-reminder-of-earlier-times-family-city/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1990s the airport focused on attracting foreign airlines.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 17, 1997 |title=Las Vegas aims high with international plan |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/nov/17/las-vegas-aims-high-with-international-plan/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005149/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/nov/17/las-vegas-aims-high-with-international-plan/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> In 1994, [[Condor Flugdienst]] began charter flights from Germany, launching scheduled service from [[Cologne]] and [[Frankfurt]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |date=March 3, 1997 |title=Condor Begins Nonstop Service to McCarran Airport |url=http://www.travelweekly.com/Travel-News/Airline-News/Condor-Begins-Nonstop-Service-to-McCarran-Airport/ |work=[[Travel Weekly]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005318/http://www.travelweekly.com/Travel-News/Airline-News/Condor-Begins-Nonstop-Service-to-McCarran-Airport/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> [[Northwest Airlines]] and [[Japan Airlines]] introduced flights from [[Tokyo]] in 1998,<ref>{{cite news |date=April 8, 1998 |title=Nonstop flights from Vegas to Japan to begin |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/apr/08/nonstop-flights-from-vegas-to-japan-to-begin/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005406/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/apr/08/nonstop-flights-from-vegas-to-japan-to-begin/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=June 6, 2011 |title=Velotta: Delta creates buzz with in-flight magazine section on Las Vegas |url=http://vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2011/jun/06/walk-walk/ |work=Vegas Inc |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609194302/http://vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2011/jun/06/walk-walk/ |archive-date=June 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Virgin Atlantic]] began flying from [[Gatwick Airport|London\u2013Gatwick]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 8, 2000 |title=Inaugural London flight arrives today |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/jun/08/inaugural-london-flight-arrives-today/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222110/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/jun/08/inaugural-london-flight-arrives-today/ |archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Innovation and D Gates completion (1997\u20132011)===\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas MD-83 (DC-9-83), Allegiant Air AN1531779.jpg|thumb|The finished D Gates in May 2009, with Terminal 3 under construction in the background]]\nIn 1997, the airport introduced Common Use Terminal Equipment (CUTE), becoming the first airport in the country to do so.<ref name=\"belliotti\">{{cite report |author=Rick Belliotti |date=2008 |title=Airport Cooperative Research Program (ACRP) Synthesis 8: Common Use Facilities and Equipment at Airports |url=http://onlinepubs.trb.org/onlinepubs/acrp/acrp_syn_008.pdf |publisher=[[Transportation Research Board]] |pages=13, 67 |accessdate=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705165616/http://onlinepubs.trb.org/onlinepubs/acrp/acrp_syn_008.pdf |archivedate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> With multiple airlines serving McCarran, it became inefficient to have separate facilities for each airline.<ref name=\"nytcute\">{{cite news |last=Stellin |first=Susan |date=November 7, 2011 |title=Sharing Catches On at Airports |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/08/business/at-airports-a-new-strategy-is-catching-on-sharing.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614135538/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/08/business/at-airports-a-new-strategy-is-catching-on-sharing.html |archive-date=June 14, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> CUTE allows for shared use of ticket counters and gates; an airline can overflow to inactive facilities during peak times.<ref name=\"nytcute\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=September 15, 1997 |title=Growing pains bring expansion to local airport |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/sep/15/growing-pains-bring-expansion-to-local-airport/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005507/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/sep/15/growing-pains-bring-expansion-to-local-airport/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMcCarran furthered its common use strategy in 2003 with the SpeedCheck system, introducing [[Common-use self-service|Common-Use Self-Service]] (CUSS) kiosks.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 20, 2003 |title=McCarran debuting 'SpeedCheck' kiosks |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2003/may/20/mccarran-debuting-speedcheck-kiosks/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005538/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2003/may/20/mccarran-debuting-speedcheck-kiosks/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> The kiosks allow passengers to check-in and print boarding passes for any one of multiple airlines. Previously, airlines had been installing their own check-in kiosks, defeating the use of CUTE and increasing congestion at the ticket counters.<ref name=\"belliotti\"/> SpeedCheck kiosks have been installed at the [[Las Vegas Convention Center]] as well.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=David |date=February 3, 2004 |title=Speeding Flight Check-In At Self-Service Kiosks |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/03/business/business-travel-speeding-flight-check-in-at-self-service-kiosks.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528015049/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/03/business/business-travel-speeding-flight-check-in-at-self-service-kiosks.html |archive-date=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2005 McCarran began offering complimentary [[Wi-Fi]] throughout its passenger terminals.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 4, 2005 |title=Las Vegas airport offering free Wi-Fi Internet connections |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/wireless/data/2005-01-04-vegas-wi-fi_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005700/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/wireless/data/2005-01-04-vegas-wi-fi_x.htm |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> The service initially covered {{convert|1.7|e6sqft|m2}}, making it the largest free Wi-Fi zone among U.S. airports at the time.<ref>{{cite press release |last=Sanchez |first=Elaine |date=January 4, 2005 |title=McCarran Launches Country\u2019s Largest Free Airport Wireless Network |url=http://cms.mccarran.com/dsweb/Get/Document-72108/01_04_05_WiFi.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019043658/http://cms.mccarran.com/dsweb/Get/Document-72108/01_04_05_WiFi.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 19, 2013 |location=Las Vegas, NV |publisher=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 1, 2016 }}</ref> The northeast wing of the D Gates opened in April 2005, along with a {{convert|160|ft}} [[air traffic control]] tower at the center of the concourse.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 15, 2005 |title=New D gates set to open today |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2005/apr/15/new-d-gates-set-to-open-today/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304112505/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2005/apr/15/new-d-gates-set-to-open-today/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> The expansion had been postponed following the [[September 11 attacks]] but resumed amid high growth in passenger traffic.<ref>{{cite press release |last=Sanchez |first=Elaine |date=April 15, 2005 |title=McCarran International Airport Showcases First Major Construction Project Since 9/11 |url=http://cms.mccarran.com/dsweb/Get/Document-83042/4_05%20D%20Gates%20NE%20Wing%20Opens.pdf |publisher=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610021238/http://cms.mccarran.com/dsweb/Get/Document-83042/4_05%20D%20Gates%20NE%20Wing%20Opens.pdf |archivedate=June 10, 2016 }}</ref> Later in the year, the airport started a baggage-tracking system using [[radio-frequency identification]] (RFID) tags.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=Mary |date=October 25, 2005 |title=McCarran Airport RFID System Takes Off |url=http://www.rfidjournal.com/articles/view?1949 |work=[[RFID Journal]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005816/http://www.rfidjournal.com/articles/view?1949 |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> Small RFID transmitters are inserted into [[bag tag|baggage tags]] to improve bag identification, thereby lowering the risk for lost or misplaced luggage. McCarran became one of the first airports worldwide to conduct RFID tagging on a large scale.<ref>{{cite news |last=West |first=Karen |date=October 13, 2006 |title=Vegas bets on radio chips for luggage problems |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15235999/ns/business-us_business/t/vegas-bets-radio-chips-luggage-problems/#.Vyabx0df3IV |work=[[MSNBC]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503005846/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15235999/ns/business-us_business/t/vegas-bets-radio-chips-luggage-problems/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 19, 2008 [[US Airways]] closed its night-flight hub at McCarran Airport,<ref name=\"aug19\">{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=April 30, 2008 |title=US Airways to cut more Las Vegas flights |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2008/apr/30/us-airways-aims-cut-more-vegas-flights/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304221639/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2008/apr/30/us-airways-aims-cut-more-vegas-flights/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> which had been established by predecessor [[America West Airlines]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |last=McCartney |first=Scott |date=March 17, 1996 |title=Grabbing The Red-eye |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-03-17/travel/9603170084_1_alliance-with-continental-airlines-america-west-airlines-david-bonderman |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812151820/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-03-17/travel/9603170084_1_alliance-with-continental-airlines-america-west-airlines-david-bonderman |archive-date=August 12, 2015}}</ref> In order to maximize the use of its fleet,<ref>{{cite news |date=February 20, 1998 |title=America West says its committed to Vegas |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/feb/20/america-west-says-its-committed-to-vegas/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503010008/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/feb/20/america-west-says-its-committed-to-vegas/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> US Airways had been operating two banks of flights to and from McCarran in the middle of the night.<ref name=\"aug19\"/> The operation had made US Airways the second-busiest carrier at McCarran, providing over 100 daily round-trip flights.<ref name=\"aug19\"/> However, amid [[2000s energy crisis|rising oil prices]] and continued demand for low fares, the airline decided to close the hub.<ref name=\"aug19\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Gilbertson |first=Dawn |date=June 13, 2008 |title=US Airways cutting jobs, flights, adding fees |url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2008/06/13/20080613biz-usairwayscuts0613.html |work=[[The Arizona Republic|azcentral.com]] |access-date=May 1, 2016}}</ref> In 2011, US Airways reduced flights to Las Vegas by an additional 40%.<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=September 1, 2011 |title=US Airways to cut 40 percent of Las Vegas flights |url=http://vegasinc.com/news/2011/sep/01/us-airways-cut-40-percent-las-vegas-flights/ |work=Vegas Inc |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609194158/http://vegasinc.com/news/2011/sep/01/us-airways-cut-40-percent-las-vegas-flights/ |archive-date=June 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008 the northwest wing of the D Gates was completed.{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=15}} This marked the completion of the concourse, which has a total of 44 gates.<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=December 14, 2008 |title=A flier's guide to McCarran |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2008/dec/14/fliers-guide-mccarran/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304075547/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2008/dec/14/fliers-guide-mccarran/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LAS LAS VEGAS TOWER CONTROL (10509713443).jpg|thumb|right|New tower under construction, July 2013]]\nIn May 2011 construction began on a new [[air traffic control]] tower. The tower is {{convert|352|ft}} tall and replaces a shorter tower that opened in 1983.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Reiley |first=Tim |date=May 31, 2011 |title=McCarran's new air traffic control tower will stand twice as tall as current one |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/mccarrans-new-air-traffic-control-tower-will-stand-twice-tall-current-one |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816212742/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/mccarrans-new-air-traffic-control-tower-will-stand-twice-tall-current-one |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In January 2014 it was discovered that a chemical coating to prevent the growth of a [[Stachybotrys chartarum|toxic fungus]] was added improperly.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Velotta |first1=Richard |last2=Rogers |first2=Keith |date=August 7, 2014 |title=Construction mistake delays McCarran tower opening |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/las-vegas/construction-mistake-delays-mccarran-tower-opening |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816214226/http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/las-vegas/construction-mistake-delays-mccarran-tower-opening |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The problem was corrected by the following June,<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=June 9, 2015 |title=FAA chief expects new McCarran tower to be operational in '16 |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/faa-chief-expects-new-mccarran-tower-be-operational-16 |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613070445/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/faa-chief-expects-new-mccarran-tower-be-operational-16 |archive-date=June 13, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and the tower opened on August 28, 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news3lv.com/news/local/mccarran-air-traffic-controllers-begin-use-of-new-control-tower | title=McCarran air traffic controllers begin using new $99M control tower | work=[[KSNV]] | date=August 28, 2016 | accessdate=September 3, 2016 | author=Clemons, Marvin | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901120021/http://news3lv.com/news/local/mccarran-air-traffic-controllers-begin-use-of-new-control-tower | archive-date=September 1, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The shorter tower will be closed and demolished.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/new-mccarran-air-traffic-control-tower-debut-aug-28 | title=New McCarran air traffic control tower to debut Aug. 28 | work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | date=July 10, 2016 | accessdate=July 24, 2016 | author=Marroquin, Art | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714175945/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/new-mccarran-air-traffic-control-tower-debut-aug-28 | archive-date=July 14, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 3 and later developments (2012\u2013present)===\nTerminal 3 opened on June 27, 2012.<ref name=\"june27\">{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=June 27, 2012 |title=McCarran\u2019s Terminal 3 opens with Vegas-style fanfare |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/jun/27/mccarrans-terminal-3-opens-vegas-style-fanfare/?_ga=1.233683356.30740358.1461886618 |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806161114/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/jun/27/mccarrans-terminal-3-opens-vegas-style-fanfare/?_ga=1.233683356.30740358.1461886618 |archive-date=August 6, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The project was announced in January 2001 as a way to accommodate rapid growth in passenger traffic, including international traffic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Packer |first=Adrienne |date=January 5, 2001 |title=International tourism fuels expansion at airport |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/jan/05/international-tourism-fuels-expansion-at-airport/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503010221/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/jan/05/international-tourism-fuels-expansion-at-airport/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> It came into question amid the [[Great Recession|2008 recession]] and decreased tourism to Las Vegas, but the county decided to proceed with the project, in anticipation of eventual economic recovery and a rebound in passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Randall |date=August 10, 2010 |title=Why we're building that new terminal at McCarran |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2010/aug/10/why-were-building-new-terminal-mccarran/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806160804/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2010/aug/10/why-were-building-new-terminal-mccarran/ |archive-date=August 6, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Terminal 3 cost $2.4 billion to build and is one of the largest [[public works]] projects in Nevada.<ref name=\"june27\"/>{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=13}} It replaced Terminal 2, providing more international gates and a larger [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] facility.<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=June 16, 2011 |title=When new terminal opens at McCarran, old one will come down |url=http://vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2011/jun/16/when-new-terminal-opens-mccarran-old-one-will-come/ |work=Vegas Inc |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609193255/http://vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2011/jun/16/when-new-terminal-opens-mccarran-old-one-will-come/ |archive-date=June 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> With its seven domestic gates, the terminal also eases congestion at Terminal 1.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Reiley |first=Tim |date=June 24, 2012 |title=McCarran embraces spacious new Terminal 3 |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/mccarran-embraces-spacious-new-terminal-3 |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630114230/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/mccarran-embraces-spacious-new-terminal-3 |archive-date=June 30, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=February 16, 2012 |title=McCarran's Terminal 3: A model gateway |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/feb/16/mccarrans-terminal-3-model-gateway/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806160101/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/feb/16/mccarrans-terminal-3-model-gateway/ |archive-date=August 6, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn a $51 million project, eight domestic gates in the D Gates were converted to seven \"swing\" gates, capable of receiving both domestic and international flights. The gates were connected to the customs facility in Terminal 3 by an underground pedestrian passageway. The project was completed in June 2017.<ref name=\"dgatesintl\">{{cite news | url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/new-corridor-linking-gates-to-inspections-area-opening-soon-at-mccarran/ | title=New corridor linking gates to inspections area opening soon at McCarran | work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] | date=May 26, 2017 | accessdate=June 3, 2017 | author=Marroquin, Art | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024042703/https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/new-corridor-linking-gates-to-inspections-area-opening-soon-at-mccarran/ | archive-date=October 24, 2017 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In addition, a $30 million renovation of Terminal 1's ticketing and baggage claim areas is underway as of December 2016. Improvements include refurbished bathrooms, new ticket counters, and [[terrazzo]] flooring.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2016/dec/25/mccarran-international-airport-by-the-numbers/|title=Las Vegas airport by the numbers|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]|author=Kudialis, Chris|date=December 25, 2016|accessdate=June 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023231137/https://lasvegassun.com/news/2016/dec/25/mccarran-international-airport-by-the-numbers/|archive-date=October 23, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, there have been attempts to rename the airport. Former U.S. Senator [[Harry Reid]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/aug/25/harry-reid-pat-mccarrans-name-shouldnt-be-anything/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013132305/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/aug/25/harry-reid-pat-mccarrans-name-shouldnt-be-anything/ |archive-date=2016-10-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Clark County Commission]]er [[Tick Segerblom]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/political/move-over-mccarran-state-lawmaker-wants-to-rename-airport-after-harry-reid |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811045047/https://www.ktnv.com/news/political/move-over-mccarran-state-lawmaker-wants-to-rename-airport-after-harry-reid |archive-date=2019-08-11 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-mccarran-nevada-2017-story.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701134039/http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-mccarran-nevada-2017-story.html |archive-date=2018-07-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[List of governors of Nevada|Nevada Governor]] [[Steve Sisolak]] - all Democrats - are currently pushing for a name change.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/nevada/sisolak-urges-renaming-las-vegas-airport-after-harry-reid-1531908/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702154659/https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/nevada/sisolak-urges-renaming-las-vegas-airport-after-harry-reid-1531908/ |archive-date=2019-07-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> The proposed names are '''Harry Reid Las Vegas International Airport''' and '''Las Vegas International Airport'''.\n\nThe airport control tower was closed for several days in 2020 after a controller tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. Airport operations continue using [[common traffic advisory frequency]], though many flights are delayed or cancelled due to reduced capacity.<ref>https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/mccarran-operations-still-slowed-as-control-tower-remains-closed-1986865/</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n===Runways===\n[[File:McCarran Terminal 1(A,B).jpg|thumb|Terminal 1, showing Concourses A and B. Concourse C extends to the right, out of view in 2011.]]\n[[File:LAS Terminal 3, March 2015.JPG|thumb|Check-in hall in Terminal 3 in 2015]]\n[[File:McCarran International Airport (8078645881).jpg|thumb|right|Automated people mover at McCarran in 2011]]\nMcCarran Airport has four runways:<ref>{{cite web |date=May 26, 2016 |title=KLAS \u2013 McCarran International Airport |url=https://www.airnav.com/airport/KLAS |work=[[Airnav.com]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604013805/http://www.airnav.com/airport/KLAS |archive-date=June 4, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable painrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"text\" | Runway\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Length\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Width\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"text\" | [[Instrument landing system|ILS]]\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1L/19R\n| {{convert|8988|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || {{convert|150|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || 1L \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ILS Category I, with [[Distance measuring equipment|DME]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1R/19L\n| {{convert|9771|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || {{convert|150|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || {{mdash}} \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8L/26R\n| {{convert|14515|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || {{convert|150|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || 26R \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ILS Category I, with [[Distance measuring equipment|DME]] <br /> Second longest civil runway in North America\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8R/26L\n| {{convert|10525|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || {{convert|150|ft|disp=br|abbr=on}} || 26L \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ILS Category I\n|}\n\nAll runways have been resurfaced with [[concrete]], a more durable material than the previous [[asphalt]]. In April 2016, 8L/26R was the last runway to be resurfaced; it is the longest at McCarran and serves a third of the airport's traffic.<ref>{{cite press release |last=Crews |first=Christine |date=April 22, 2016 |title=McCarran Reopens Runway 8L/26R |url=http://www.clarkcountynv.gov/public-communications/news/Pages/McCarran-Reopens-Runway-8L26R.aspx |location=Las Vegas, NV |publisher=[[Clark County, Nevada]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Parallel to it is runway 8R/26L, which opened in 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spillman |first=Benjamin |date=November 15, 2008 |title=Runway work could snarl flights |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/runway-work-could-snarl-flights |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606220352/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/runway-work-could-snarl-flights}}</ref> On the western side of the airport are runways 1L/19R and 1R/19L. 1L/19R was a 5000-foot runway for light aircraft before it was widened and lengthened in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=McCarran International Airport opens a new runway for air carrier use |url=http://aviationweek.com/awin/mccarran-international-airport-opens-new-runway-air-carrier-use |work=[[Aviation Week|The Weekly of Business Aviation]] |access-date=June 6, 2016 |url-access=subscription  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606215730/http://aviationweek.com/awin/mccarran-international-airport-opens-new-runway-air-carrier-use |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Between the two sets of parallel runways was runway 14/32, which has been decommissioned.{{efn|The runway appears in [[Jeppesen]] charts from 1955 and 1966;<ref>{{cite map |title=Standard Instrument Approach Procedures; Las Vegas, Nevada; McCarran Field; LAS |date=December 6, 1955 |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8041962050/sizes/l |publisher=[[Jeppesen]] |access-date=June 19, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107171644/https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8041962050/sizes/l |archivedate=January 7, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite map |title=Jeppesen Approach Chart; Las Vegas, Nev.; McCarran Apt. |date=June 21, 1966 |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8066233386/sizes/l |publisher=[[Jeppesen]] |access-date=June 19, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107171651/https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8066233386/sizes/l |archivedate=January 7, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> it closed about 1973.}} Runways 8L/26R and 8R/26L were previously 7L/25R and 7R/25L. The runways were renumbered 8L/26R and 8R/26L in August 2017 due to a shift in direction of the Earth's magnetic field.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marroquin|first1=Art|title=Magnetic shifts prompt a renumbering for runways at McCarran|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/news-columns/road-warrior/magnetic-shifts-prompt-a-renumbering-for-runways-at-mccarran/|accessdate=August 20, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=August 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820180917/https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/news-columns/road-warrior/magnetic-shifts-prompt-a-renumbering-for-runways-at-mccarran/|archive-date=August 20, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Magnetic shifts prompt renumbering for runways at McCarran|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/article168286917.html|accessdate=August 20, 2017|work=Miami Herald|agency=The Associated Press|date=August 20, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821045744/http://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/article168286917.html|archive-date=August 21, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDry weather at McCarran allows operations under visual flying rules 99% of the time. During most of the year (about 56% of the time) the airport uses Visual Configuration 1: runways 19R and 26L for arrivals and 19L and 26R for departures. Airfield capacity in Configuration 1 is constrained by bordering military airspace, high terrain to the west, and an uphill departure from 26R. Because of the heat, 26R is favored over 19L for departures. When the winds shift in the winter (about 13% of the year), the airfield adopts Visual Configuration 3, which uses 01L and 26L for arrivals and 01L and 01R for departures. Marginal flying conditions adopt the same Configuration 1/Configuration 3 split based on the prevailing winds. In instrument weather, arrivals are preferred on 26L, and departures take off from 19L and 26R.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/profiles/media/LAS-Airport-Capacity-Profile-2015.pdf |title=McCarran International (Las Vegas) Airport Capacity Profile, 2015 |date=2015 |publisher=Federal Aviation Administration |accessdate=5 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501170813/https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/profiles/media/LAS-Airport-Capacity-Profile-2015.pdf |archive-date=1 May 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Terminals===\nThere are two terminals at McCarran and 5 concourses with a total of 92 gates. Terminal 1 was completed in 1963, Terminal 2 was completed in 1986, and Terminal 3 was completed in 2012. Prior to the completion of Terminal 3, Terminal 2 handled international flights. After Terminal 3 was completed, Terminal 2 became redundant and it was demolished in 2016.\n\n'''Terminal 1''' opened on March 15, 1963, and was expanded between 1970 and 1974 with the current A and B Gates buildings.<ref name=\"one1\"/> Currently, Terminal 1 has four concourses, each of which is connected to a central pre-security area. Ticketing and baggage claim are located on Level 1 of this area. Level 2 houses the three security checkpoints, an [[esplanade]] with several retail outlets, and a [[United Service Organizations|USO]] lounge for military service members.<ref name=\"map\">{{cite web |title=My Journey |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Fly/MyJourneyMap.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=June 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803160331/https://www.mccarran.com/Fly/MyJourneyMap.aspx |archive-date=August 3, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> West of the pre-security area are the A Gates and the B Gates, two Y-shaped concourses with circular ends. To the south are the C Gates, which can be accessed by the Green Line of the [[McCarran International Airport Automated People Movers|tram system]]. The satellite D Gates concourse, which opened in 1998, lies to the east and contains three [[airport lounge|lounges]]: the Centurion lounge for [[American Express]] card holders; the Club at LAS, which is available to all passengers at a fee; and the [[United Club]]. The Blue Line of the tram system links the D Gates with the pre-security area. Gate D22 is the only 3-jetway gate at McCarran and was reconfigured specifically to accommodate the double-decker [[Airbus A380]].<ref name=\"facilities\">{{cite web |title=Facilities & Services |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Find/FacilitiesServices.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=June 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416035233/https://www.mccarran.com/Find/FacilitiesServices.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n'''Terminal 3''' handles all international and some domestic flights. Level 0 of the terminal contains customs, baggage claim, and another USO lounge. Check-in, security, a second Club at LAS, and all gates are on Level 2.<ref name=\"facilities\" />{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=23}} The terminal has 14 gates, seven domestic (E8\u2013E12, E14\u2013E15) and the other seven international (E1\u2013E7).{{sfn|Jones|2012|page=23}} Four of the international gates have two [[jet bridge|jetways]] each to allow for quicker handling of wide-body aircraft. Passengers flying Air Canada, Frontier Airlines, Hawaiian Airlines, Sun Country Airlines, and United Airlines all check-in and receive baggage at Terminal 3, but depart out of the D gates. The Red Line of the tram system links Terminal 3 with the D Gates.<ref>{{cite web |title=Red Line Tram at McCarran International Airport |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Tram/Red |website=www.mccarran.com |accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Automated people mover===\n{{Main|McCarran International Airport Automated People Movers}}\nMcCarran has three separate tram lines:\n* Green line, connecting Terminal 1 with C Gates\n* Blue line, connecting Terminal 1 with D Gates\n* Red line, connecting Terminal 3 with D Gates\n\n===Ground transportation===\n[[File:Go to Rent A Car Center (5290042243).jpg|thumb|A shuttle about to depart Terminal 1 for the rental car center in 2010]]\nRoad access to McCarran Airport is provided by Paradise Road to the north and by the [[McCarran Airport Connector]] to the south, which connects to the [[Las Vegas Beltway]].\n\nTerminal 1 and Terminal 3 have their own parking garages.<ref>{{cite web |title=Terminal 1 \u2013 Long Term |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal1Parking/Terminal1-LongTerm.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416030845/https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal1Parking/Terminal1-LongTerm.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Terminal 3 \u2013 Long Term |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal3Parking/Terminal3-LongTerm.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417021012/https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal3Parking/Terminal3-LongTerm.aspx |archive-date=April 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Each also has its own economy lot, which provides lower parking rates,<ref>{{cite web |title=Terminal 1 \u2013 Economy Parking |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal1Parking/Terminal1-Economy.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416034034/https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal1Parking/Terminal1-Economy.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Terminal 3 \u2013 Economy Parking |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal3Parking/Terminal3-Economy.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416024528/https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal3Parking/Terminal3-Economy.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a separate lot for oversize vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Terminal 1 \u2013 Remote/Oversize Vehicle Parking |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal1Parking/Terminal1-RemoteorOversizeVehicle.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416025135/https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal1Parking/Terminal1-RemoteorOversizeVehicle.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Terminal 3 Oversize Vehicle Parking |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal3Parking/Terminal3-OversizeVehicle.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416032720/https://www.mccarran.com/Park/Terminal3Parking/Terminal3-OversizeVehicle.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Complimentary shuttle transportation is provided between the terminals and the remote Terminal 1 economy and oversize vehicle lots. In March 2016, the airport opened a [[cellphone lot]], which provides free parking to people waiting for passengers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=March 14, 2016 |title=McCarran opens cellphone parking lot for passenger pick-up |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/travel/mccarran-opens-cellphone-parking-lot-passenger-pick |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521214532/http://www.reviewjournal.com/travel/mccarran-opens-cellphone-parking-lot-passenger-pick |archive-date=May 21, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA consolidated rental car facility opened in April 2007, located about {{convert|3|mi}} from the airport. The facility, which sits on {{convert|68|acre}} of land, houses multiple rental car companies with 5,000 parking spaces on multiple levels. Courtesy shuttles transport passengers between the airport and the facility.<ref name=\"rentalcar\">{{cite news |title=Car Renters Consolidate in Building Near Airport |last=Spillman |first=Benjamin |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/car-renters-consolidate-building-near-airport |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |date=April 4, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523021526/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/car-renters-consolidate-building-near-airport |archivedate=May 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nFor transportation between Terminal 1 and Terminal 3, McCarran Airport provides a free shuttle service, which leaves from Level 0 of both terminals.<ref name=\"rtc\">{{cite web |title=Airport Transit Routes |url=http://www.rtcsnv.com/transit/getting-to-mccarran-airport/ |work=[[RTC Transit]] |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515124519/http://www.rtcsnv.com/transit/getting-to-mccarran-airport/ |archive-date=May 15, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Inter-terminal Shuttle |url=https://www.mccarran.com/Go/Inter-TerminalShuttle.aspx |work=McCarran International Airport |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416030658/https://www.mccarran.com/Go/Inter-TerminalShuttle.aspx |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[RTC Transit]] provides bus transportation to and from various parts of the Las Vegas Valley. Route 108, Route 109, the Westcliff Airport Express and the Centennial Express provide direct access to the airport. Buses depart from Level 0 of Terminal 1 and Level 2 of Terminal 3.<ref name=\"rtc\" />\n\n===Other facilities===\nA small parking lot on the south side of the airport, on E. Sunset Road, between Las Vegas Blvd., and S. Eastern Ave, allows the public to watch aircraft take off, land, and listen to the aircraft radios.  This is the only \"official\" watching area.  There are several unofficial areas, mainly off the ends of the runways, however they are heavily patrolled by Las Vegas Metro Police and spectators are commonly asked to leave.\n\n[[Atlantic Aviation]] and [[BBA Aviation|Signature Flight Support]] are the two [[fixed-base operator]]s (FBOs) at the airport, providing various services to private aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kudialis |first=Chris |date=May 1, 2015 |title=With megafight near, airport traffic peaking at record levels |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/megafight-near-airport-traffic-peaking-record-levels |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 10, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701110552/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/megafight-near-airport-traffic-peaking-record-levels |archivedate=July 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMaverick Helicopters, Sundance Helicopters, and Papillon Grand Canyon Helicopters each operate their own terminal at McCarran Airport. The Maverick terminal covers {{convert|6000|sqft}}, while the Sundance terminal occupies {{convert|13000|sqft}}. The Papillon terminal was established in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Snel |first=Alan |date=April 16, 2015 |title=Papillon marks 50th anniversary with golden helicopter |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/papillon-marks-50th-anniversary-golden-helicopter |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 14, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804190352/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/aviation/papillon-marks-50th-anniversary-golden-helicopter |archivedate=August 4, 2016 }}</ref> The companies provide helicopter tours over the [[Las Vegas Strip]], [[Grand Canyon]], and other tourist attractions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=November 20, 2015 |title=Maverick Aviation takes off with plush new Las Vegas terminal |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/maverick-aviation-takes-plush-new-las-vegas-terminal |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 10, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424004953/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/maverick-aviation-takes-plush-new-las-vegas-terminal |archivedate=April 24, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ferrara |first=David |date=April 21, 2014 |title=Sundance Helicopters remodels terminal, polishes image |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/business-press/sundance-helicopters-remodels-terminal-polishes-image |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701110555/http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/business-press/sundance-helicopters-remodels-terminal-polishes-image |archive-date=July 1, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Janet (airline)|Janet]] flights depart from a private terminal located on the west side of the airport. The airline, which is owned by the [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] and operated by [[AECOM]], transports employees and contractors to airports within the [[Nevada Test Site|Nevada National Security Site]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Matt |date=July 22, 2015 |title=U.S. government airline Janet hides in plain site |url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-ideas/weird-and-wacky/us-government-airline-janet-hides-in-plain-site/news-story/40ae596ec47d3d02b9cf0cd6704198db |work=[[News.com.au]] |access-date=May 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505122217/http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-ideas/weird-and-wacky/us-government-airline-janet-hides-in-plain-site/news-story/40ae596ec47d3d02b9cf0cd6704198db |archive-date=May 5, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Marnell Air Cargo Center covers {{convert|200928|sqft}} and can handle {{convert|100000|ST}} of cargo.<ref name=\"marnellshowsoff\">{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard |date=October 9, 2010 |title=Company shows off air cargo center |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2010/oct/09/company-shows-air-cargo-center/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208015035/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2010/oct/09/company-shows-air-cargo-center/ |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The $29 million facility opened in October 2010,<ref>{{cite news |last=Hansen |first=Kyle |date=September 9, 2010 |title=McCarran air cargo center to open in October |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2010/sep/09/mccarran-air-cargo-center-open-october/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304190723/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2010/sep/09/mccarran-air-cargo-center-open-october/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> replacing a smaller facility that existed at the site of Terminal 3.<ref name=\"marnellshowsoff\" /> The center consists of two buildings, one of which is leased by [[FedEx]] and the other by multiple other companies, including [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] and [[Southwest Airlines]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dostal |first=Erin |date=November 9, 2009 |title=Marnell breaks ground on McCarran cargo center |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2009/nov/09/marnell-breaks-ground-mccarran-cargo-center/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208013605/http://lasvegassun.com/news/2009/nov/09/marnell-breaks-ground-mccarran-cargo-center/ |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe main exhibits of the Howard W. Cannon Aviation Museum are located on Level 2 of Terminal 1, above baggage claim. There are additional exhibits throughout the airport and at other airports in the city. Display items chronicle the early history of aviation in [[Southern Nevada]].<ref name=\"clarkcounty\" /> The museum is named after former Nevada Senator [[Howard Cannon]], who contributed to the development of aviation in the county.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 3, 1999 |title=Airport museum named after former Sen. Howard Cannon |url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/jun/03/airport-museum-named-after-former-sen-howard-canno/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |access-date=May 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511032128/http://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/jun/03/airport-museum-named-after-former-sen-howard-canno/ |archive-date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> Its administrator is Mark Hall-Patton, who has appeared on the reality television show ''[[Pawn Stars]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lyle |first=Michael |date=August 9, 2011 |title=TV show makes a star out of museum administrator Mark Hall-Patton |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/life/community-organizations/tv-show-makes-star-out-museum-administrator-mark-hall-patton |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=May 10, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701104613/http://www.reviewjournal.com/life/community-organizations/tv-show-makes-star-out-museum-administrator-mark-hall-patton |archivedate=July 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list | 3rdcoltitle = Refs | 3rdcolunsortable=yes\n<!-- -->\n| [[Aerom\u00e9xico]] | [[Mexico City International Airport|Mexico City]] | <ref name=\"Aerom\u00e9xicoRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Flight Schedule|url=https://booking.aeromexico.com/SSW2010/D5DE/flightSchedulePage.html?_ga=1.18768702.686413547.1491325115|accessdate=23 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406022455/https://booking.aeromexico.com/SSW2010/D5DE/flightSchedulePage.html?_ga=1.18768702.686413547.1491325115|archive-date=6 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| {{nowrap|[[Aerom\u00e9xico Connect]]}} | [[Monterrey International Airport|Monterrey]] |<ref name=\"Aerom\u00e9xicoRoutes\" />\n<!-- --> \n| [[Air Canada Rouge]] | [[Calgary International Airport|Calgary]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau]], [[Toronto Pearson International Airport|Toronto\u2013Pearson]], [[Vancouver International Airport|Vancouver]]  | <ref name=\"Air Canada Flight Schedules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aircanada.com/ca/en/aco/home/book/routes-and-partners/flight-schedules.html|title=Flight Schedules|publisher=Air Canada|access-date=2018-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323072516/https://www.aircanada.com/ca/en/aco/home/book/routes-and-partners/flight-schedules.html|archive-date=2018-03-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Alaska Airlines]] | [[Paine Field|