{"title_page": "Reference class forecasting", "text_new": "{{context|date=November 2010}}\n'''Reference class forecasting''' or '''comparison class forecasting''' is a method of predicting the future by looking at similar past situations and their outcomes. The theories behind reference class forecasting were developed by [[Daniel Kahneman]] and [[Amos Tversky]]. The theoretical work helped Kahneman win the [[Nobel Prize in Economics]].\n\nReference class [[forecasting]] is so named as it predicts the outcome of a planned action based on actual outcomes in a reference class of similar actions to that being forecast. \n\nDiscussion of which reference class to use when forecasting a given situation is known as the [[reference class problem]].\n\n==Overview==\n\nKahneman and Tversky<ref name=\"Kahneman and Tversky 1979\">{{cite journal|last1=Kahneman|first1=Daniel|last2=Tversky|first2=Amos|title=Prospect Theory: An Analysis of Decision under Risk|journal=Econometrica|date=1979|volume=47|issue=2|pages=263\u2013291|doi=10.2307/1914185|url=https://www.princeton.edu/~kahneman/docs/Publications/prospect_theory.pdf|jstor=1914185|citeseerx=10.1.1.407.1910}}</ref><ref name=\"Kahneman and Tversky 1977\">{{cite journal|title=Intuitive prediction: Biases and corrective procedures|url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a047747.pdf|date=1977|last1=Kahneman |first1=Daniel|last2=Tversky|first2=Amos}} Decision Research Technical Report PTR-1042-77-6. In\n{{cite book|editor-last1=Kahneman|editor-first1=Daniel|editor-last2=Slovic|editor-first2=Paul|editor-last3=Tversky|editor-first3=Amos\n|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511809477.031\n|title=Judgment Under Uncertainty: Heuristics and Biases\n|pages=414\u2013421\n|year=1982\n|isbn=9780511809477\n|chapter=Intuitive prediction: Biases and corrective procedures|last1=Kahneman|first1=Daniel|last2=Tversky|first2=Amos}}</ref> found that human judgment is generally [[Optimism bias|optimistic]] due to overconfidence and insufficient consideration of distributional information about outcomes. \n\nPeople tend to underestimate the costs, completion times, and risks of planned actions, whereas they tend to overestimate the benefits of those same actions. Such error is caused by actors taking an \"'''inside view'''\", where focus is on the constituents of the specific planned action instead of on the actual outcomes of similar ventures that have already been completed.\n\nKahneman and Tversky concluded that disregard of distributional information, i.e. risk, is perhaps the major source of error in forecasting. On that basis they recommended that forecasters \"should therefore make every effort to frame the forecasting problem so as to facilitate utilizing all the distributional information that is available\".<ref name=\"Kahneman and Tversky 1977\" />{{rp|416}}  Using distributional information from previous ventures similar to the one being forecast is called taking an \"'''outside view'''\".  Reference class forecasting is a method for taking an outside view on planned actions.\n\nReference class forecasting for a specific project involves the following three steps:\n# Identify a reference class of past, similar projects.\n# Establish a [[probability distribution]] for the selected reference class for the [[parameter]] that is being forecast.\n# Compare the specific project with the reference class distribution, in order to establish the most likely outcome for the specific project.\n\n== Reference class tennis ==\nThe [[reference class problem]], also known as reference class tennis, is the discussion of which reference class to use when forecasting a given situation. \n\nSuppose someone were trying to predict how long it would take to write a psychology textbook. Reference class tennis would involve debating whether we should take the average of all books (closest to an outside view), just all textbooks, or just all psychology textbooks (closest to an inside view).<ref name=\"Conceptually\">{{cite news|title=Week 10: Reference Class Forecasting|url=https://conceptually.org/concepts/reference-class-forecasting/|work=[[Conceptually]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lw\">{{cite news|title=Outside view|url=https://wiki.lesswrong.com/wiki/Outside_view|work=[[LessWrong Wiki]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Practical use in policy and planning==\n\nWhereas Kahneman and Tversky developed the theories of reference class forecasting, [[Flyvbjerg]] and [[COWI]] (2004) developed the method for its practical use in policy and planning. The first instance of reference class forecasting in practice is described in Flyvbjerg (2006).<ref name=\"Flyvbjerg2006\">{{cite journal|first1=Bent|last1= Flyvbjerg|date=2006|title=From Nobel Prize to Project Management: Getting Risks Right|journal=Project Management Journal|volume=37|issue=3|pages= 5\u201315|arxiv=1302.3642|ssrn=2238013|bibcode=2013arXiv1302.3642F|doi= 10.1177/875697280603700302}}</ref> This was a forecast carried out in 2004 by the UK government of the projected capital costs for an extension of [[Edinburgh Trams]]. The promoter's forecast estimated a cost of \u00a3255 million. Taking all available distributional information into account, based on a reference class of comparable rail projects, the reference class forecast estimated a cost of \u00a3320 million.  A report issued in August 2011 estimated that the final cost of the yet unfinished project would be over \u00a31 billion, for a shorter tram line than the proposed Line 2.<ref name=bbc-loan>{{cite news|title=Council to borrow \u00a3231m for Edinburgh trams project|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14594872|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 August 2011|date=19 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the Edinburgh forecast, reference class forecasting has been applied to numerous other projects in the UK, including the \u00a315 (US$29) billion [[Crossrail]] project in London. After 2004, The Netherlands, Denmark, and Switzerland have also implemented various types of reference class forecasting.\n\nBefore this, in 2001 (updated in 2011), [[AACE International]] (the Association for the Advancement of Cost Engineering) included Estimate Validation as a distinct step in the recommended practice of Cost Estimating (Estimate Validation is equivalent to Reference class forecasting in that it calls for separate empirical-based evaluations to benchmark the base estimate):\n\n<blockquote>\nThe estimate should be benchmarked or validated against or compared to historical experience and/or past estimates of the enterprise and of competitive enterprises to check its appropriateness, competitiveness, and to identify improvement opportunities...Validation examines the estimate from a different perspective and using different metrics than are used in estimate preparation.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160530211731/http://www.aacei.org/tcmfree/tcmframework_webedition.pdf AACE International, \"Total Cost Management Framework, Section 7.3, Cost Estimating and Budgeting\", 2011. p. 147]</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn the process industries (e.g., oil and gas, chemicals, mining, energy, etc. which tend to dominate AACE's membership), benchmarking (i.e., \"outside view\") of project cost estimates against the historical costs of completed projects of similar types, including probabilistic information, has a long history.<ref>Merrow, E. and Yarossi, M., \"[http://search.proquest.com/openview/42daeef9f8c368ef28f3434d206eeb93/1.pdf Assessing Project Cost and Schedule Risk]\", 1990 AACE Transactions. pp H.6.1-7</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Business and economics}}\n*[[Base rate fallacy]]\n*[[Benefit shortfall]]\n*[[Consensus forecast]]\n*[[Cost overrun]]\n*[[Event chain methodology]]\n*[[Financial risk]]\n*[[Forecasting]]\n*[[Hofstadter's Law]]\n*[[Optimism bias]]\n*[[Planning fallacy]]\n*[[Reference class problem]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal|pmid=12858711 |year=2003 |last1=Lovallo |first1=D |title=Delusions of success. How optimism undermines executives' decisions |journal=Harvard Business Review |volume=81 |issue=7 |pages=56\u201363 |last2=Kahneman |first2=D  |url=https://hbr.org/2003/07/delusions-of-success-how-optimism-undermines-executives-decisions}}\n*{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tenILJ-MowQC&pg=PA133|title=Decision-making on Mega-Projects|isbn=9781848440173|editor-last1=Priemus|editor-first1=Hugo|editor-last2=Flyvbjerg|editor-first2=Bent|editor-last3=van Wee|editor-first3=Bert|date=2008|doi=10.4337/9781848440173.00014|chapter=Public Planning of Mega-Projects: Overestimation of Demand and Underestimation of Costs|last1=Flyvbjerg|first1=Bent}}\n*{{cite book|doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199563142.003.0014|year=2011|last1=Flyvbjerg|first1=Bent|chapter=Over Budget, Over Time, Over and Over Again: Managing Major Projects|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=FI7l8O1tlkkC&pg=PT321|title=The Oxford Handbook of Project Management|isbn=9780199563142|editor-last1=Morris|editor-first1=Peter W. G|editor-last2=Pinto|editor-first2=Jeffrey K|editor-last3=S\u00f6derlund|editor-first3=Jonas|editor-link3=Jonas S\u00f6derlund}}\n\n\n[[Category:Evaluation methods]]\n[[Category:Economic forecasting]]\n[[Category:Prediction]]\n", "text_old": "{{context|date=November 2010}}\n'''Reference class forecasting''' or '''comparison class forecasting''' is a method of predicting the future by looking at similar past situations and their outcomes. The theories behind reference class forecasting were developed by [[Daniel Kahneman]] and [[Amos Tversky]]. The theoretical work helped Kahneman win the [[Nobel Prize in Economics]].\n\nReference class [[forecasting]] is so named as it predicts the outcome of a planned action based on actual outcomes in a reference class of similar actions to that being forecast. \n\nDiscussion of which reference class to use when forecasting a given situation is known as the [[reference class problem]].\n\n==Overview==\n\nKahneman and Tversky<ref name=\"Kahneman and Tversky 1979\">{{cite journal|last1=Kahneman|first1=Daniel|last2=Tversky|first2=Amos|title=Prospect Theory: An Analysis of Decision under Risk|journal=Econometrica|date=1979|volume=47|issue=2|pages=263\u2013291|doi=10.2307/1914185|url=https://www.princeton.edu/~kahneman/docs/Publications/prospect_theory.pdf|jstor=1914185|citeseerx=10.1.1.407.1910}}</ref><ref name=\"Kahneman and Tversky 1977\">{{cite journal|title=Intuitive prediction: Biases and corrective procedures|url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a047747.pdf|date=1977|last1=Kahneman |first1=Daniel|last2=Tversky|first2=Amos}} Decision Research Technical Report PTR-1042-77-6. In\n{{cite book|editor-last1=Kahneman|editor-first1=Daniel|editor-last2=Slovic|editor-first2=Paul|editor-last3=Tversky|editor-first3=Amos\n|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511809477.031\n|title=Judgment Under Uncertainty: Heuristics and Biases\n|pages=414\u2013421\n|year=1982\n|isbn=9780511809477\n|chapter=Intuitive prediction: Biases and corrective procedures|last1=Kahneman|first1=Daniel|last2=Tversky|first2=Amos}}</ref> found that human judgment is generally [[Optimism bias|optimistic]] due to overconfidence and insufficient consideration of distributional information about outcomes. \n\nPeople tend to underestimate the costs, completion times, and risks of planned actions, whereas they tend to overestimate the benefits of those same actions. Such error is caused by actors taking an \"'''inside view'''\", where focus is on the constituents of the specific planned action instead of on the actual outcomes of similar ventures that have already been completed.\n\nKahneman and Tversky concluded that disregard of distributional information, i.e. risk, is perhaps the major source of error in forecasting. On that basis they recommended that forecasters \"should therefore make every effort to frame the forecasting problem so as to facilitate utilizing all the distributional information that is available\".<ref name=\"Kahneman and Tversky 1977\" />{{rp|416}}  Using distributional information from previous ventures similar to the one being forecast is called taking an \"'''outside view'''\".  Reference class forecasting is a method for taking an outside view on planned actions.\n\nReference class forecasting for a specific project involves the following three steps:\n# Identify a reference class of past, similar projects.\n# Establish a [[probability distribution]] for the selected reference class for the [[parameter]] that is being forecast.\n# Compare the specific project with the reference class distribution, in order to establish the most likely outcome for the specific project.\n\n== Reference Class Tennis ==\nThe [[reference class problem]], also known as reference class tennis, is the discussion of which reference class to use when forecasting a given situation. \n\nSuppose someone were trying to predict how long it would take to write a psychology textbook. Reference class tennis would involve debating whether we should take the average of all books (closest to an outside view), just all textbooks, or just all psychology textbooks (closest to an inside view).<ref name=\"Conceptually\">{{cite news|title=Week 10: Reference Class Forecasting|url=https://conceptually.org/concepts/reference-class-forecasting/|work=[[Conceptually]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lw\">{{cite news|title=Outside view|url=https://wiki.lesswrong.com/wiki/Outside_view|work=[[LessWrong Wiki]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Practical use in policy and planning==\n\nWhereas Kahneman and Tversky developed the theories of reference class forecasting, [[Flyvbjerg]] and [[COWI]] (2004) developed the method for its practical use in policy and planning. The first instance of reference class forecasting in practice is described in Flyvbjerg (2006).<ref name=\"Flyvbjerg2006\">{{cite journal|first1=Bent|last1= Flyvbjerg|date=2006|title=From Nobel Prize to Project Management: Getting Risks Right|journal=Project Management Journal|volume=37|issue=3|pages= 5\u201315|arxiv=1302.3642|ssrn=2238013|bibcode=2013arXiv1302.3642F|doi= 10.1177/875697280603700302}}</ref> This was a forecast carried out in 2004 by the UK government of the projected capital costs for an extension of [[Edinburgh Trams]]. The promoter's forecast estimated a cost of \u00a3255 million. Taking all available distributional information into account, based on a reference class of comparable rail projects, the reference class forecast estimated a cost of \u00a3320 million.  A report issued in August 2011 estimated that the final cost of the yet unfinished project would be over \u00a31 billion, for a shorter tram line than the proposed Line 2.<ref name=bbc-loan>{{cite news|title=Council to borrow \u00a3231m for Edinburgh trams project|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14594872|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 August 2011|date=19 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the Edinburgh forecast, reference class forecasting has been applied to numerous other projects in the UK, including the \u00a315 (US$29) billion [[Crossrail]] project in London. After 2004, The Netherlands, Denmark, and Switzerland have also implemented various types of reference class forecasting.\n\nBefore this, in 2001 (updated in 2011), [[AACE International]] (the Association for the Advancement of Cost Engineering) included Estimate Validation as a distinct step in the recommended practice of Cost Estimating (Estimate Validation is equivalent to Reference class forecasting in that it calls for separate empirical-based evaluations to benchmark the base estimate):\n\n<blockquote>\nThe estimate should be benchmarked or validated against or compared to historical experience and/or past estimates of the enterprise and of competitive enterprises to check its appropriateness, competitiveness, and to identify improvement opportunities...Validation examines the estimate from a different perspective and using different metrics than are used in estimate preparation.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160530211731/http://www.aacei.org/tcmfree/tcmframework_webedition.pdf AACE International, \"Total Cost Management Framework, Section 7.3, Cost Estimating and Budgeting\", 2011. p. 147]</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn the process industries (e.g., oil and gas, chemicals, mining, energy, etc. which tend to dominate AACE's membership), benchmarking (i.e., \"outside view\") of project cost estimates against the historical costs of completed projects of similar types, including probabilistic information, has a long history.<ref>Merrow, E. and Yarossi, M., \"[http://search.proquest.com/openview/42daeef9f8c368ef28f3434d206eeb93/1.pdf Assessing Project Cost and Schedule Risk]\", 1990 AACE Transactions. pp H.6.1-7</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Business and economics}}\n*[[Base rate fallacy]]\n*[[Benefit shortfall]]\n*[[Consensus forecast]]\n*[[Cost overrun]]\n*[[Event chain methodology]]\n*[[Financial risk]]\n*[[Forecasting]]\n*[[Hofstadter's Law]]\n*[[Optimism bias]]\n*[[Planning fallacy]]\n*[[Reference class problem]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal|pmid=12858711 |year=2003 |last1=Lovallo |first1=D |title=Delusions of success. How optimism undermines executives' decisions |journal=Harvard Business Review |volume=81 |issue=7 |pages=56\u201363 |last2=Kahneman |first2=D  |url=https://hbr.org/2003/07/delusions-of-success-how-optimism-undermines-executives-decisions}}\n*{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tenILJ-MowQC&pg=PA133|title=Decision-making on Mega-Projects|isbn=9781848440173|editor-last1=Priemus|editor-first1=Hugo|editor-last2=Flyvbjerg|editor-first2=Bent|editor-last3=van Wee|editor-first3=Bert|date=2008|doi=10.4337/9781848440173.00014|chapter=Public Planning of Mega-Projects: Overestimation of Demand and Underestimation of Costs|last1=Flyvbjerg|first1=Bent}}\n*{{cite book|doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199563142.003.0014|year=2011|last1=Flyvbjerg|first1=Bent|chapter=Over Budget, Over Time, Over and Over Again: Managing Major Projects|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=FI7l8O1tlkkC&pg=PT321|title=The Oxford Handbook of Project Management|isbn=9780199563142|editor-last1=Morris|editor-first1=Peter W. G|editor-last2=Pinto|editor-first2=Jeffrey K|editor-last3=S\u00f6derlund|editor-first3=Jonas|editor-link3=Jonas S\u00f6derlund}}\n\n\n[[Category:Evaluation methods]]\n[[Category:Economic forecasting]]\n[[Category:Prediction]]\n", "name_user": "Me, Myself, and I are Here", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReference Class Tennis:cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_class_forecasting"}
{"title_page": "Last Farewell (Big Bang song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Last Farewell\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Big Bang (South Korean band)|Big Bang]]\n| album      = [[Hot Issue (EP)|''Hot Issue'']]\n| released   = November 22, 2007\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Electronic dance music]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 3:52\n| label      = [[YG Entertainment]]\n| writer     = [[G-Dragon]], [[Brave Brothers]]\n| producer   = [[G-Dragon]], [[Brave Brothers]]\n| prev_title = Always\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = How Gee\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\n\n\"'''Last Farewell'''\" ([[Hangul|Korean]]: {{lang|ko|\ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \uc778\uc0ac}}; [[Revised Romanization of Korean|Revised Romanization]]: ''Majimak Insa'') is a song by [[South Korea]]n [[boy band]] [[Big Bang (South Korean band)|Big Bang]].  It was released through [[YG Entertainment]] on November 22, 2007 as the lead single from the quintet's second [[extended play]] [[Hot Issue (EP)|''Hot Issue'']].  The song was written by [[G-Dragon]] and composed by the member and [[Brave Brothers]].  Mirroring the success of the group's preceding single \"[[Lies (Big Bang song)|Lies]],\" the song went on to become a chart topper.\n\n== Background and composition ==\nWith the release of their first extended play, [[Always (EP)|''Always'']] in 2007, Big Bang began to experiment more with their sound, moving away from their original [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] roots, and experimenting with [[electronic music]] and [[dance music]]. Their second EP, ''[[Hot Issue (EP)|Hot Issue]]'', released that same year, built on that its predecessor's momentum.<ref name=\":0\"/> \"Last Farewell,\" the lead single, was described by [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] as one of the most blatant pop songs in the group's repertoire, with a \"trance-tinged hip pop\" sound.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7633039/bigbang-best-songs|title=The 10 Best BIGBANG Songs: Critics' Picks|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> ''KpopStarz'' noted that the single included \"some of the clubbiest sounds seen from Big Bang up until this point\".<ref name=\"kpopstarz\"/> A Japanese-language version of the song named \"Baby Baby\" was included in the quintet's first and second Japanese albums ''[[Number 1 (Big Bang album)|Number 1]]'' and ''[[Big Bang (2009 album)|Big Bang]]'', as well in their [[greatest hits album]] ''[[The Best of Big Bang 2006-2014]]''. \n\n=== Controversies ===\nThe involvement of G-Dragon in writing and composing the melody \u2013 as it was unusual at the time for members of a band to be so involved in the production of their album<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/04/30/2009043000853.html|title=\uc591\ud604\uc11d, \ube45\ubc45 \uad8c\uc9c0\uc6a9 \uc791\uace1  \ub17c\ub780 \ud574\uba85|language=ko|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> \u2013 raised questions by [[netizen]]s over how much the rapper actually produced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/04/30/2009043001315.html|title='\ube45\ubc45' \uc9c0\ub4dc\ub798\uace4(G-Dragon), \uc791\uace1 \uc2e4\ub825 \uacfc\uc7a5\ub41c \ud64d\ubcf4?|last=Kim|first=Young-ro|date=2009-04-30|work=The Chosun Ilbo|language=ko|access-date=2017-01-19|via=}}</ref>  [[Yang Hyun-suk]], founder and CEO of YG Entertainment, went on to clarify that G-Dragon wrote and compose the music, with arrangements done by long-time collaborator Brave Brothers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://h21.hani.co.kr/arti/culture/culture_general/24956.html|title=[\ub9c8\uc74c\uc740 \uc5b8\uc81c\ub098 \ub85d\uc2a4\ud0c0]\uc544\uc774\ub3cc \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc640 \u2018\uacf5\ub3d9 \uc791\uace1\uc790\u2019|last=Jeong|first=Minyoung|date=2009-05-13|website=|publisher=The Hankyoreh|language=ko|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2009/08/this-artist-copied-big-bang|title=This Artist Copied Big Bang? {{!}} allkpop.com|newspaper=allkpop|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2009/07/brave-brothers-album-to-feature-big-bang-and-son-dambi|title=Brave Brothers' Album to Feature Big Bang and Son Dambi {{!}} allkpop.com|newspaper=allkpop|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref>\n\nThe success of Big Bang spawned the creation of OkBang, a Chinese group whose music and looks were similar to the former.<ref name=\"Copycat of Big Bang Surfaces in China\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/12/135_57613.html|title=Copycat of Big Bang Surfaces in China|date=2009-12-20|author=|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=2008-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and recognition==\nReception for \"Last Farewell\" was positive, with Tamar Herman of ''Billboard'' ranking it at number nine in the magazine's list of ten best Big Bang songs, writing that the single \"hits all the right notes to be quintessential K-pop song: catchy chorus, swoon-worthy crooning, and a pump-up dance beat.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Park Hyo-jae from ''[[The Chosun Ilbo]]'' praised its \"addictive chorus\" and \"sophisticated electronic sound\", commenting that the song being written by a member of the group set Big Bang apart from the other idols. Park also complimented the group's stage fashion, noting that their use of high top sneakers and skinny jeans, as well as their hair styles, had become a trend among teenagers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://choen.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/02/19/2009021901460.html|title=[\ube453 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc \uae30\ud68d\uc0ac \uc9d1\uc911 \ubd84\uc11d] \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\ub3c4 \uc2a4\uc2a4\ub85c \uc74c\uc545\uc744 \ub9cc\ub4e4\uc5b4\uc57c \ud55c\ub2e4. - \uc870\uc5d4 CHOEN|last=Park|first=Hyo-jae|date=2009-02-22|website=choen.chosun.com|publisher=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> The single's choreography, especially the [[jump rope]] movement, became a national phenomenon in South Korea.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2007120811191544749&type=3 |title=\ube45\ubc45, '\uc904\ub118\uae30\ucda4'\uc73c\ub85c \uad6d\ubbfc\ub304\uc2a4 \ub3c4\uc804\n |work=Star News |date=December 8, 2007 |accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> \"Last Farewell\" is recognized as one of the group's definitive songs, for setting the direction they would eventually go in on songs like \"[[Fantastic Baby]]\" and \"[[Bang Bang Bang (Big Bang song)|Bang Bang Bang]]\".<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\"kpopstarz\">{{citeweb|url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/233485/20150823/big-bang-best-songs.htm|title=K-Pop Mixtape: 9 Most Definitive Big Bang Songs|accessdate=2017-02-16|website=KpopStarz.}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Last Farewell\" was released prior to the creation of the [[Gaon Music Chart]], which began tracking music performance in 2010. The song topped various charts from online music services upon its release, including the [[Melon (online music service)|Melon]] chart for eight consecutive weeks, holding the record for longest-running number-one song by a boy group.<ref name=\"\ube45\ubc45 \uc96c\ud06c\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8 8\uc8fc \uc5f0\uc18d 1\uc704 \uae30\uc5fc, JOO\ub3c4 2\uc8fc\ub9cc\uc5d0 7\uc704 \uc9c4\uc785\">{{cite web|title=[M+\uae30\ud68d\u2026'\ubcf4\uc774\uadf8\ub8f9 \ud1b5\uacc4'\u2461] \ucd5c\uc7a5\u00b7\ucd5c\ub2e4 \uc74c\uc6d0 1\uc704 \ube45\ubc45, \uacac\uc904 \uadf8\ub8f9 \uc5c6\ub2e4 |last=Park |first=Jung Sun |work=MBN Daily|date=May 7, 2014 |url=http://www.mbn.co.kr/pages/news/newsView.php?news_seq_no=1778998 |accessdate=July 29, 2017 |language=ko  }}</ref> At another music service [[CJ E&M Music Performance Division|Mnet.com]], the single remained at the first spot for six weeks, a record for the time.<ref name=\"mnet\">{{citeweb|url= http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2008010809113244837&type=3|work=Star News |date=January 8, 2008 |accessdate=December 21, 2017|title=\ube45\ubc45, \uc2f8\uc774\uc6d4\ub4dc '\uc774\ub2ec\uc758\ub178\ub798' 3\uad00\uc655}}</ref> \"Last Farewell\" went to be awarded Song of the Month (December) in the 2008 [[Cyworld Digital Music Awards]], recording 170,000 copies sold that month.<ref name=\"mnet\"/><ref name=\"LFAREWELL/CYWORLD/SOM\"> {{cite web|url=http://music.cyworld.com/chart/chart_dma_list.asp?curMonth=200712|title=Song of the Month|year=2007|work=Cyworld|accessdate=2010-01-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725172714/http://music.cyworld.com/chart/chart_dma_list.asp?curMonth=200712|archivedate=2011-07-25}}</ref> The single was the fourth best-performing song of the 2000s (decade) in Melon, the highest entry by a male group.<ref>{{citeweb|url =http://www.melon.com/chart/age/index.htm?chartType=AG&chartGenre=KPOP&chartDate=2000#params%5Bidx%5D=1 |title=The 2000s |accessdate=February 20, 2017 |publisher=Melon Music Chart}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Arrangement\n| title1 = Last Farewell\n| note1 = \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \uc778\uc0ac; Majimak Insa<ref name=\":2\">{{citeweb|url=http://www.qobuz.com/fr-fr/album/hot-issue-bigbang/3610153734041 |title=Hot Issue - BIGBANG |work=[[Qobuz]]|accessdate=2017-02-28|language=fr}}</ref>\n| length1 = 3:52\n| lyrics1 = G-Dragon\n| music1 = G-Dragon, Brave Brothers\n| extra1 = Brave Brothers\n}}\n\n== Charts and sales ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Chart !! Peak<br />position  \n|-\n| [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet Music Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 1<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://m.inews24.com/view.php?g_serial=305862&g_menu=700100|title=\uc544\uc774\ub274\uc2a424 \ubaa8\ubc14\uc77c|last=Bak|first=Jaedeok|date=2008-01-08|website=\uc544\uc774\ub274\uc2a424|publisher=Joy News|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Melon Music Awards|Melon Music Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 1<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n| [[Cyworld Digital Music Awards|Cyworld Music Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 1<ref name=\":1\" />\n|}\n\n=== Sales ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Chart'''\n!'''Sales'''\n|-\n|South Korea\n|5,128,203<ref>Cumulative sales for \"Last Farewell\" since 2011:\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=12&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2011 \u2013 Week  12|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002073913/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=12&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=13&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2011 \u2013 Week  13|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002074401/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=13&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=29&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2011 \u2013 Week  29|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002073357/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=29&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=30&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2011 \u2013 Week  30|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002073123/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2011&targetTime=30&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=3&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=09&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2012 \u2013 Week 09|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002072310/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=3&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=09&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=2&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=10&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2012 \u2013 Week 10|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002072806/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=2&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=10&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=3&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=11&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2012 \u2013 Week 11|work=Gaon Chart}}{{dead link|date=September 2017|fix-attempted=yes}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=14&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2012 \u2013 Week  14|work=Gaon Chart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002072529/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=14&nationGbn=K |archivedate = October 2, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=15&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2012 \u2013 Week  15|work=Gaon Chart}}{{dead link|date=September 2017|fix-attempted=yes}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?pageno=4&serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2012&targetTime=16&nationGbn=K|title=Gaon Download Chart 2012 \u2013 Week  16|work=Gaon Chart}}{{d